First, we can factor the terms in the denominator: $$\frac{1}{n(n+1)} = \frac{1}{n} - \frac{1}{n+1}$$ We can use this to write the sum in a telescoping form: \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{12} + \cdots + \frac{1}{n(n+1)} + \cdots + \frac{1}{9900} &= \left(1 -\frac{1}{2}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{3} - \frac{1}{4}\right) + \cdots + \left(\frac{1}{99}-\frac{1}{100}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{100}-\frac{1}{101}\right)\\
&= 1 - \frac{1}{101}\\
&= \boxed{\frac{100}{101}}
\end{align*}

We can rewrite each term as $\frac{1}{n(n+1)} = \frac{1}{n}-\frac{1}{n+1}$ using partial fractions. Then, we can telescope the sum as follows:
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{12} + \cdots + \frac{1}{n(n+1)} +\cdots + \frac{1}{9900} &= \left(1-\frac{1}{2}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{3}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{3}-\frac{1}{4}\right) + \cdots + \left(\frac{1}{99}-\frac{1}{100}\right) \\
&= 1-\frac{1}{100} \\
&= \boxed{\frac{99}{100}}.
\end{align*}

