Since the monic polynomial $p(x)$ has degree 4 and the roots 1, 2, and 3, we have that $$p(x) = (x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-a)$$ for some constant $a$. We want to find $p(0) + p(4)$. We can note that $p(x)$ has the form $$(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-a) = ((x-2)^2-1)((x-2)-1)((x-2)+1)(x-a).$$ Expanding this, we get \begin{align*}
p(x) &= ((x-2)^2-1)((x-2)-1)((x-2)+1)(x-a) \\
&= (x-2)^2(x-3)(x-1)(x-a) - (x-2)(x-1)(x+1)(x-a) \\
&= (x-2)(x-1)(x-a)(x-3).
\end{align*}

Now we can use this factorization to find $p(0)$ and $p(4)$ as follows:
\begin{align*}
p(0) &= (0-2)(0-1)(0-a)(0-3) = 6a, \\
p(4) &= (4-2)(4-1)(4-a)(4-3) = 6(1-a).
\end{align*}
Thus, we have that $$p(0)+p(4) = 6a + 6(1-a) = 6.$$ Therefore, the final answer is $\boxed{6}$.

