We know that $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ are even functions, so $f(-x) = f(x)$ and $g(-x) = g(x)$ for all $x$. 

Consider the product $f(x)g(x)$. We have:

\begin{align*}
(f(x)g(x))(-x) &= f(-x)g(-x) \quad \text{(using the definition of function negation)}\\
&= f(x)g(x) \quad \text{(using the evenness of $f(x)$ and $g(x)$)}
